Attachment A UNIT POWER SALES AGREEMENT
THIS AGREEMENT, made and entered into, this 18th day of December, 1984, and modified on January 31, 2020, by and between Dominion Energy South Carolina, Inc. (?DESC?) and South Carolina Generating Company, Inc. (?GENCO?),
WITNESSETH THAT:
WHEREAS, GENCO was incorporated on October 1, 1984, under the laws of the State of South Carolina and will own Williams Electric Generating Station (?Williams Station?) as of December 31, 1984; and
WHEREAS, DESC owns and operates electric generating, transmission and distribution facilities in South Carolina, and generates, transmits and sells electric energy both at retail and wholesale in such state; and
WHEREAS, GENCO has agreed to sell to DESC the entire capacity and energy from Williams Station and DESC has agreed to join with GENCO in executing an agreement which sets forth in detail the terms and conditions for the sale of such capacity and energy by GENCO to DESC; and
WHEREAS, GENCO and DESC executed an Operating Agreement on December 18, 1984, containing the terms and conditions whereby DESC provides all services required by GENCO for the operation of the Williams Station; and
WHEREAS, GENCO and DESC desire to integrate the terms and conditions of the Operating Agreement into Attachment A-1 to this Agreement and, after such time as this Agreement is accepted for filing by the FERC, to terminate the Operating Agreement; and
WHEREAS, the Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017, which reduced the corporate income tax from a maximum of 35% to a flat 21%, became effective on January 1, 2018; and
WHEREAS, GENCO and South Carolina Electric & Gas Company (?SCE&G?) originally entered into this Agreement on December 18, 1984, and SCE&G subsequently changed its name to DESC on April 29, 2019.
NOW, THEREFORE, GENCO and DESC agree as follows:
1.0 Recitals
1.1 GENCO shall, subject to the terms and conditions of this Agreement, make available, or cause to be made available, to DESC all of the capacity and energy from Williams Station.
1.2 DESC shall, subject to the terms and conditions of this Agreement, purchase, and shall be entitled to receive, all of the capacity and energy from Williams Station.
1.3 Commencing on January 1, 1985, and continuing monthly thereafter until this Agreement is terminated pursuant to the provisions of Section 10 hereof, in consideration of the right to receive the full output of Williams Station, DESC will pay GENCO an amount equal to GENCO?s Total Cost of Service for Williams Station for each month.
2.0 Definitions
2.1 ?Williams Station? is a 580 MW coal fired electric generating plant located in Bushy Park, South Carolina.
2.2. ?FERC? shall mean the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission or any successor governmental authority.
2.3 ?Uniform System of Accounts? shall mean the Uniform System of Accounts prescribed by the FERC for Class A and Class B Public Utilities and Licenses, as in effect from time to time.
2.4 ?Operating Expenses? shall include, but not be limited to, (a) all amounts chargeable to GENCO?s operating expense accounts, less any applicable credits thereto, in accordance with the Uniform System of Accounts; (b) depreciation accrued at a rate at least sufficient to fully amortize the non-salvageable plant investment, including the cost of removal of interim retirements, over the estimated then remaining useful life of Williams Station; and (c) any and all taxes imposed on the Company by local, state and/or federal authorities.
2.5 ?Net Investment? for any month shall be computed as of the last day of the previous month and shall consist of (a) the aggregate amount chargeable at the time in accordance with the Uniform System of Accounts to GENCO?s utility plant accounts less the balance at the time of any accumulated provision for depreciation and amortization of utility plant, as determined in accordance with the Uniform System of Accounts, plus (b) the aggregate amount chargeable at the time for materials and supplies (including fuel stock) in accordance with the Uniform System of Accounts; plus (c) reasonable allowances for prepaid items and cash working capital; and less (d) accumulated provision for deferred income taxes.
2.6 ?Capital Cost? for any month shall be that computed as of the last day of the previous month (?computation date?). Capital Cost as of a computation date shall be the sum of (a) fifteen percent (15%) multiplied by the ratio which the Equity Investment, as of such date, is to the Total Capital as of such date; plus (b) the ?effective interest rate? per annum of each principal amount of debt (other than loans or advances made by the common stockholder of GENCO) outstanding on such date for money borrowed, multiplied by the ratio which such principal amount is to Total Capital as of such date; plus (c) the ?effective dividend rate? per annum of each series of preferred stock outstanding as of such date multiplied by the ratio which the amount at which such preferred stock would be reflected on a balance sheet of GENCO is to Total Capital as of such date. The ?effective interest rate? of each principal amount of debt referred to in (b) will reflect the annual interest requirements and to the extent applicable, amortization of issue expenses, discounts and premiums, sinking fund call premiums, expenses and discounts, refunding and retirement expenses, discounts and premiums, and all other expenses applicable to the issue of such indebtedness. The ?effective dividend rate? of each series of preferred stock referred to in (c) will reflect the annual dividend requirements applicable to each such series of preferred stock.
2.7 ?Equity Investment? as of any date shall consist of the sum of (a) all amounts paid to GENCO for all common capital stock theretofore issued, plus all capital contributions, advances or pro rate loans pursuant to any capital contribution agreement, less the sum of any amounts paid by GENCO to its common stockholder in the form of stock retirements, repurchases or redemptions, return of capital or repayments of such advances or loans, plus (b) any credit balance (i) in the paid-in capital account not included under (a) and (ii) in the retained earnings account on the books of GENCO as of such date.
2.8 ?Total Capital? as of any date shall be the Equity Investment plus the total of all other securities, debt and preferred stock then outstanding.
2.9 ?Total Cost of Service? for any month shall be the sum of (a) GENCO?s Operating Expenses for such month for Williams Station plus (b) an amount equal to one-twelfth of the Capital Cost multiplied by the Net Investment for Williams Station.
3.0 The performance of the obligations of GENCO under this Agreement shall be subject to the receipt and continued effectiveness of all authorizations of governmental regulatory authorities at the time necessary to permit GENCO to perform its duties and obligations hereunder, including the operations of Williams Station, and for GENCO to make available to DESC all of the capacity and energy from Williams Station. GENCO shall use its best efforts to secure and maintain all such authorizations by governmental regulatory authorities.
4.0 GENCO shall be responsible for the operation and maintenance of Williams Station in accordance with good utility practice and Attachment A-1 to this Agreement. Outages for inspection, maintenance, repairs and replacements shall be scheduled in accordance with good utility practice and, insofar as practicable, shall be mutually agreed to by GENCO and DESC.
5.0 Delivery of capacity and energy to DESC pursuant to this Agreement shall occur at the point of interconnection of DESC transmission facilities and GENCO?s generating facilities and shall be made in the form of three-phase, 60 hertz alternating current as a nominal voltage of 20.0 kilovolts. GENCO will supply and maintain all necessary metering equipment for determining the quantity and conditions of delivery under t6his Agreement. GENCO will furnish to DESC such summaries of meter readings and other metering information as many reasonable by requested.
6.0 Monthly bills shall be calculated in accordance with the provisions of this Agreement as soon after the beginning of each month as practicable and shall be payable on or before the 15th day of such month.
7.0 Nothing contained herein shall be construed as affecting in any way the right of GENCO unilaterally to make application to FERC for a change in the rates contained herein or any other term or condition of this Agreement under Section 205 of the Federal Power Act and pursuant to FERC Rules and Regulations promulgated thereunder.
8.0 DESC shall not be entitled to set off against any payment required to be made by it under this Agreement (a) any amounts owed by GENCO to DESC or (b) the amount of any claim by DESC against GENCO. The foregoing, however, shall not affect in any other way the rights and remedies of DESC with respect to any such amounts owed to DESC by GENCO or any such claim by DESC against GENCO.
9.0 The invalidity and unenforceability of any provision of this Agreement shall not affect the remaining provisions hereof.
10.0 This Agreement shall continue until terminated by mutual agreement to the parties hereto.
11.0 DESC and GENCO may, subject to the provisions of this Agreement, enter into a further agreement or agreement between DESC and GENCO, setting forth detailed terms and provisions relating to the performance by DESC and GENCO of their respective obligations under this Agreement. No agreement entered into under this Section 11 shall, however, alter to any substantive degree the obligations of any party to this Agreement in any manner inconsistent with any of the foregoing sections of this Agreement.
12.0 The agreements herein set forth have been made for the benefit of DESC and GENCO and their respective successors and assigns and no other person shall acquire or have any right under or by virtue of this Agreement.
13.0 This Agreement shall be binding upon the parties hereto and their successors and assigns, but no assignment hereof, or of any right to any funds due or to become due under this Agreement, shall in any event relieve either DESC or GENCO of any of their respective obligations hereunder, or, in the case of DESC, reduce to the extent its entitlement to receive all of the capacity and energy from Williams Station.
IN WITNESS WHEREOF, the parties hereto have caused this Agreement to be duly executed as of the day and year first above written.

Attachment A-1 OPERATION AND MAINTENANCE PROVISIONS
1. GENCO hereby appoints DESC as Operator of the Williams Station, and DESC hereby accepts such appointment and agrees to provide to GENCO in connection with the operation and maintenance of the Williams Station the supervisory, administrative and technical services hereinafter stipulated to be provided by DESC in an efficient and economical manner and in accordance with sound and prudent practices employed in the industry and in compliance with all valid and applicable laws, rules and regulations of governmental authorities.
2. Services to be Performed. Subject to the limitations set forth the in this Agreement, DESC shall perform on behalf of GENCO, and as may be directed by GENCO in writing from time to time and accepted in writing by DESC, all services and duties necessary to the operation of the Williams Station, including, but not limited to, the following:
a. To keep and maintain all books, accounts and records for GENCO in accordance with generally accepted accounting principles applicable to a regulated utility; b. To operate the Williams Station to generate electricity to be delivered to DESC?s transmission system; c. To determine the dispatch of energy from Williams Station to DESC; d. To provide purchasing services for GENCO, as necessary, and to perform such services on behalf of GENCO; e. To keep an accurate account of all transactions on behalf of GENCO for which DESC is responsible and, whenever requested by GENCO, promptly preparing and submitting to GENCO reports and other information in such form and detail as GENCO may reasonably request; f. To investigate, report and make recommendations to GENCO concerning all claims or litigation filed by or against GENCO; g. To perform for GENCO maintenance services including, but not limited to the following: 1. Supervision and inspection of maintenance work. 2. Labor and technical services. 3. Maintenance of generating equipment, including boilers, turbines, generators, and auxiliary equipment. 4. Maintenance of electrical equipment and devices. 5. Maintenance of control equipment, computers and other control devices. 6. Maintenance of metering facilities. 7. Maintenance of coal handling equipment. 8. Maintenance of buildings, structures, fences and other facilities at Williams Station. h. To provide for GENCO engineering and construction services including, but not limited to, the following: 1. Engineering, supervision, and inspection of construction work. 2. Construction, labor and supervision as may be required. 3. Other engineering and construction services as may from time to time be mutually agreed upon. i. To act as agent for GENCO in the procurement and scheduling of delivery of coal and other fuels to Williams Station, including, but not limited to, the administration of all of GENCO?s contract rights and obligations under any coal purchase contracts or coal transportation contracts. j. To furnish all prudent and necessary services in addition to those enumerated herein, as support for the efficient operation and maintenance of Williams Station.
3. Manner of Performance by DESC. DESC shall perform all operating services for GENCO under this Agreement in a good workmanlike manner, using competent and capable employees, and will operate the Williams Station in accordance with sound and prudent industry practices in accordance with all applicable laws and regulations. GENCO shall have the right to consult with DESC in connection with DESC?s performance of its operating obligations under the Agreement.
4. Cost Reimbursement. As included in the formula in Attachment B to this Agreement, GENCO will reimburse DESC monthly for the following listed costs and expenses:
a. Salaries, wages (including payroll taxes) and insurance and other employee benefits paid to DESC?s employees engaged in carrying out the obligations of DESC under this Agreement; b. Reasonable expenses incurred by DESC?s employees in the performance of their duties for GENCO and for which such employees would be reimbursed by DESC. c. All rentals paid by DESC in performing its obligations under this Agreement; d. The cost of transportation of DESC?s employees and equipment. The cost for automobiles and trucks owed by DESC and used under this Agreement will be billed to GENCO at DESC?s standard rates; e. The cost of contract services and utilities procured from outside sources for performance by DESC under this Agreement; f. All taxes assessed or levied upon or incurred or paid by DESC in connection with DESC?s operation of the Williams Station; g. All other reasonable costs incurred by DESC necessary to carry out the obligations under this Agreement.
5. Indemnity by GENCO. GENCO hereby agrees to indemnify and hold DESC harmless from and against any and all claims, liabilities, expenses, costs, demand or causes of action for injury to or death of employees or agents of GENCO, if any, and for damage to or destruction of GENCO?s owned or leased property arising out of, in connection with, or as an incident to any good faith act or omission of DESC or of its employees pursuant to this Attachment A-1; save and except only such acts or omissions of DESC or its employees as constitute sole negligence, bad faith or willful misconduct.
6. Indemnity by DESC. DESC hereby agrees to indemnify and hold GENCO harmless from and against any and all claims, liabilities, expenses, costs, demand or causes of action for injury to or death of employees or agents of DESC and for damage to or destruction of property of DESC arising out of, in connection with, or as an incident to the performance by DESC of its obligations under this Attachment A-1; save and except only such acts or omissions of GENCO or its employees as constitute sole negligence, bad faith or willful misconduct.
7. Insurance. In addition to the indemnity provided in Paragraph 6 above, DESC agrees to carry and maintain at all times while DESC is obligated to perform operating services under this Agreement, Worker?s Compensation and Employer?s Liability Insurance covering the employees of DESC or its agents engaged in performing services hereunder, in compliance with all applicable state and federal laws, with the limits of such insurance (which may include self-insurance) to be in such amounts as GENCO and DESC shall from time to time agree upon, but not less than the minimum insurance required by law. DESC will provide for property and liability insurance for the Williams Station facilities operated by DESC and such cost thereof be reimbursed by GENCO.
8. Force Majeure. If by reason of force majeure either Party hereto is rendered unable, wholly or in part, to carry out its obligations under this Attachment A-1, and if such Party gives notice and reasonably full particulars of such force majeure in writing which shall be furnished to the other within a reasonable time after the occurrence of the cause relied on, the Party giving such notice, so far as and to the extent that it is affected by such force majeure, shall not be liable in damages during the continuance of any liability so caused; provided, such cause shall be remedied with all reasonable dispatch.
9. Force Majeure Defined. As used in Section 8 of this Attachment A-1, force majeure shall mean acts of God, strikes, lockouts or other industrial disturbances, acts of a public enemy, wars, blockades, insurrections, riots, epidemics, landslides, lightning, earthquakes, fires, storms (including, but not limited to, hurricanes or hurricane warnings), crevasses, floods, washouts, arrests and restraints of the government, either federal or state, civil or military, civil disturbances, shutdowns for purposes necessary repairs, relocation or construction of facilities, breakage or accident to machinery or lines, the necessity for testing (as required by governmental authority or as deemed necessary by the testing party for the safe operation thereof), the necessity of making repairs or alteration to equipment, accidents, breakdowns, inability of either Party hereto to obtain necessary material, supplies or permits, or labor to perform or comply with any obligation or condition of this Agreement, rights-of-way, and any other causes, whether of the kid herein enumerated or otherwise, which are not reasonably in control of the Party claiming suspension. It is understood and agreed that the settlement of strikes or lockouts shall be entirely within the discretion of DESC and that the above reasonable dispatch shall not require the settlement of strikes or lockouts by acceding to the demands of any opposing party when such course is inadvisable in the discretion of DESC.
10. Limitations. Such force majeure affecting the performance under this Attachment A-1 by either Party, however, shall not relive such Party of liability in the event of failure to use due diligence to remedy the situation and to remove the cause in an adequate manner and with all reasonable dispatch, nor shall such causes or contingencies affecting such performance relieve such Party from its obligations to make payments as determined hereunder.
11. Audit. GENCO shall have the right to audit DESC?s books and records. Such audit will be conducted by an independent Certified Public Accounting firm mutually agreed to by the Parties. 12. Governmental Regulations. This Agreement is subject to all present and future valid orders, rules and regulations of regulatory agencies of the Federal Government and the State of South Carolina.
13. Regulatory Reports. DESC shall provide to GENCO reports and data necessary for GENCO to file with any State or Federal regulatory agency.
14. Notice. Any notice, request, demand, statement, invoice, bill or payment provided for or permitted under this Attachment A-1, or any notice which either party shall desire to give to the other, shall be in writing, if time permits, and otherwise shall be verbal and promptly followed by a written notice.
15. Independent Contractor. In the performance of the obligations under this Agreement, DESC shall be an independent contractor and not an employee or agent of GENCO.

SOUTH CAROLINA GENERATING COMPANY, INC. WILLIAMS STATION DEPRECIATION STUDY
Williams Station
Williams Station, a 611,000 kilowatt Electric generating station, was constructed on a 470 acre tract of land located in the northern half of Bushy Park industrial area near Charleston, South Carolina.
The plant began commercial operation in June, 1973 with a rated net capacity of 580 megawatts and originally was designed to operate as a base load plant using No. 6 fuel oil as its fuel source. Bushy Park is a peninsula formed by the Cooper River and the Back River, a parallel stream. Bushy Park is in Berkeley County approximately ten miles from the urbanized area of Charleston, and can be reached by barge from the Charleston Harbor through a channel running up the Cooper River.
Oil for the plant was brought by barge from Charleston harbor to a dock on the Cooper River side of the plant and pumped through 12-inch pipes to storage tanks.
Condenser cooling water is drawn from the Back River and is circulated through the condensers which change the water back into a liquid state to be used again.
On September 13, 1982, the Company entered into a Construction Contract with the J.E. Sirrine Company for the conversion of the Williams Station from oil-fired to coal-fired operation because of the economic advantage of coal as compared to oil. The Construction Contract is for a fixed sum subject to certain adjustments.
Page 2
The conversion contract provides for modifications to the boiler including the removals and additions to the boiler to convert it to a pulverized coal?fired unit operation. Equipment affected is in the fuel transport system, air and gas transport systems, windbox and burners, economizer, boiler circulation system oilfires, sootblowers, and control systems. Auxiliary systems are also included, such as cooling water and compressed air, necessary for reliable operation of the unit on pulverized coal.
The conversion of Williams Station from oil to pulverized coal operation require the installation of various ash handling subsystems. Electrostatic precipitators were installed in order to meet required air quality standards.
A coal handling system including car dumpers, conveyors, coal crushers and bunker have been installed with necessary civil work, electrical and instrumentation.
The Company has also performed work to upgrade the existing plant, purchased a coal dozer, locomotive, ash pond site, and has made other physical improvements to extend the plant life.
The plant began coal-fired operation in June, 1984. The Construction Contract with J.E. Sirrine Company is due and payable December 31, 1984.
Page 3 Depreciation Practices I. General Utility plant and equipment is constantly changing. New construction techniques, installation of new and different property units, environmental considerations and pollution control requirements all contribute to change which directly affects average service lives, mortality patterns and net salvage expectations.
It is necessary to monitor the dynamics of change through periodic depreciation studies and to make the adjustments necessary to provide for an adequate capital recovery program. The results of the study conducted by Plant Accounting personnel have been reviewed and agreed to by Gilbert Associates, Inc., an independent engineering consulting firm.
II. Procedures Used Depreciation acquires added significance and complexity in capital intensive industries. A series of statistical computer programs are employed to assist in life estimation and are described in subsequent paragraphs.
A. Theoretical Reserve Calculations With Trending (Y604) The Accumulated Provision for Depreciation Ledgers at Dominion Energy South Carolina, Inc. are maintained at a functional level for most facilities with the exception of licensed projects, which are required by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission to be maintained on a location basis, steam plants and other production units. This program has the ability to calculate a theoretical reserve for each account or subaccount based on a specific mortality curve. This theoretical reserve is the basis for allocation of the actual reserve to the account level.
A theoretical reserve is that amount of depreciation which would have accumulated if the average service life and mortality predictions now being considered had been recognized at the origination of the account and the retirement activity in the account had followed this pattern.
B. Forecast Program (Y802) Utilities have many different types of properties such as production plants, individual structures, and certain transmission facilities which are likely to be retired in total at one point in time. For example, once major equipment such as boilers and generators are worn beyond repair in a steam plant, the remaining facilities will be of little use. Consequently, the whole steam plant will likely be taken out of service at that time. For some facilities the absence of a feedstock at some point in time would necessitate the retirement of those facilities. Page 4
The most important factor in the forecast analysis is the projected retirement date for a specific facility. Another factor of importance is the amount of interim retirement activity of retirements prior to complete retirement.
Once the projected retirement date is determined, there is a specified span of years in which to recover the investments of given ages. The program will calculate the average service life, annual accrual, and theoretical reserve for each surviving vintage. Interim retirements will have different service lives and must be calculated individually. The sum of the annual provisions and the survivors are used to determine a weighted average service life for the investment group.
C. Cost of Removal & Salvage Program (P109) The estimate of net salvage is a vital part of a depreciation study. Before depreciation rates can be established, proper consideration must be given to net salvage percentages in order to determine whether the accruals must be increased to provide for net cost of removal or must be decreased where salvage recovery from the retired property sold will exceed cost of removal.
Unlike retirements, gross salvage and cost of removal are extremely difficult to analyze at the primary plant account level. Often net salvage amounts are assigned to work orders with retirements occurring from several different plant account. There is no indication as to which plant accounts these net salvage amounts are related. Consequently, using the available data, some method must be used to split net salvage amounts between accounts. Currently, net salvage accounts are assigned on a dollar basis according to the retirements applicable.
A salvage analysis is designed to determine as close as possible the normal net salvage expectations. Any abnormal transactions occurring that would distort the results have been purged or their source identified.
III. Analysis of Results: Additional information regarding the analyses performed, interpretation of data, assumptions made, pertinent projected information and the rationale used in selection of the annual depreciation accrual rates are contained in the following section:
Steam Production Consistent with the procedures followed in previous studies, the average service life, average remaining life and theoretical depreciation reserve were developed in current study using harmonically weighted analysis with a projected terminal date. Page 5
The projected retirement date for Williams Station represents the best current estimate of the total life spans by the Company engineers in Power Operations. Projected retirement date has been revised. The life span estimate has been increased fourteen years which is reflective of the Company?s intention to keep existing units in service longer because of the tremendously increasing cost of constructing new base load units.
Extending the service life of an existing fossil fuel unit will necessitate significant interim additions and retirements to maintain operating efficiency. Company engineers have indicated that a concentrated effort will be made over the next ten years to upgrade and retrofit existing plants. Analysis of the Construction Forecast indicates likely expenditures and replacements through 1993. Because an extension of service life has been made, additional interim retirements have been projected beyond 1993 to the terminal date of the particular plant. Beyond 1987 forecasted retirements are of a general nature. History indicates that minimal retirements may be expected from the structures account (A/C 311). Based upon engineering judgement the non-specific interim retirements are assumed to apply in the following manner: 50% from Boiler Plant (A/C 312), 30% from Turbogenerator (A/C 314), 10% from Accessory Electric Equipment (A/C 315) and 10% from Miscellaneous Power Plant Equipment (A/C 316). In the opinion of Gilbert Associates these assignments are reasonable and reflect a conservative position. A schedule of interim retirements forecast for Williams Station is included in subsequent paragraphs.
Williams has one oil-fired unit which operates at supercritical pressure producing 580 megawatts net summer capability.
The unit is currently being retrofitted to burn pulverized coal under a turnkey contract and is expected to be operational in 1984.
In order to measure the impact of the conversion upon the Williams Steam Plant depreciation rates, the contract costs together with peripheral expenditures to be made by the Company have been incorporated in the analysis shown on page 7.
Interim retirements of $1,572,400 in the Boiler account are forecast in connection with the coal conversion work. Other interim retirements expected to occur prior to final retirement to amount to over $3 million.
Because of the conversion to coal-fired, Williams Station is expected to have a 35 year span life extension, according to Company engineers, to the year 2019. This results in a remaining life rate of 2.66% as shown on the Schedule of Indicated Remaining Life Accrual Rates.
Page 6 INTERIM RETIREMENTS
Company engineers have projected the retirement dates for fossil fuel generating units in the system. Consistent with the current Company philosophy of curtailment in construction of new generating facilities, the expected service life of existing plants, including Williams Station, has been extended beyond the terminal date previously forecast.
In order to economically operate a generating plant 5-10 years longer, it will be necessary for the Company to expend considerable dollars for maintenance, renewals and replacements.
